	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=17147&mid=103771739575381>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=17147&mid=103771739575381>RE: nice</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=17147&mid=103771739575381#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Nov 19th 10:11 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=174826><span id= >Xalion</span></a><br><span id=notbold>27 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>He's talking about a Dragon Points System or something similiar.&nbsp;&nbsp;Basically, you are awarded points for every raid/guild event you attend.  When an item drops, instead of a guild leader deciding who it goes to or randoming it, if you want it you bid a certain number of points.  The person bidding the most points gets the item.  Once you have won an item, you lose the points you bid.<br><br>This works well for many of the high end raiding guild because it encourages attendance and tends to let loot get distributed among the right classes.  People don't want to waste their points so they tend not to bid on &quot;nice&quot; items, they only bid on something they really want.  It also ends arguments about &quot;I've been here longer, I deserve it&quot; or &quot;That random was unfair, give it to me&quot; type of thing - arguments that can arrise in guilds that focus purely on equipment and raiding.  I believe most of the high end guilds use a system similar to this.<br><br>Xalion Buscador<br>54 Heretic of Xev</p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
